&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by[bold] Dr[bold] P[bold]eter[bold] Nelson [OLS 0012][bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]PORNOGRAPHY: BRITAIN’S BIG PROBLEM[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A young man walks into a newsagent and buys a copy of the 
[normal]Sun
[normal] or similar newspaper.  On page 3, he sees a picture of a young woman wearing little or no clothing.  What goes through his mind?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Does he think, ‘I must get a good job, earn a living, save some money, get married, have children, and help bring them up’?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Or does he think, ‘I must go out at the weekend, have some drinks, find a woman, and have sex with her’?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If the latter is the case, then society has a big problem.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Consequences[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]In the 
[normal]first
[normal] place, young men who think like this do not make good fathers.  They make women pregnant, but take little or no interest in bringing up the children.  This leaves women bringing up children on their own.  While some do this remarkably well, the evidence is that children from single-parent families do less well, and are less well-behaved, at 
[normal]school.
[normal]1
[normal]  Even
[normal] in homes where a father is present, there can be domestic violence which has an adverse effect on children.  Many of the problems in education today can be traced back to poor parenting.  Teaching youngsters who lack discipline and encouragement to study is very difficult.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Secondly
[normal], the open display of sex in the media brings sex to the attention of children from an early age.  This leads them to engage in sexual activities before they are old enough to appreciate the consequences.  Teenage pregnancy rates in Britain are very high.  This is despite attempts to bring them down by promoting the use of contraceptives in 
[normal]schools.
[normal]2
[normal]  These
[normal] fail because they raise children’s interest in sex still further.  Even good sex education is limited in what it can do, given the big influence the media have on young people.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A recent NSPCC study reveals that nine out of ten young people between 13 and 17 years old in England, Scotland, and Wales have experienced some form of intimate relationship.
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thirdly
[normal], pornography encourages men to be promiscuous.  Promiscuity leads to transmission of sexually transmitted-diseases (SDIs).  Health agencies promote the use of condoms to try to stop this, but condoms are not always used, and frequently fail.  SDI levels in Britain are very high and rising.  The number of new diagnoses in the UK is now running at 1.3% of the population per year.
[normal]4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fourthly
[normal], pornography inflames men’s sexual passions.  Men who cannot control these may attack women.  The incidence of rape and indecent assault on women in Britain is very high.  On present figures, one in ten women will be raped or assaulted during their lifetime.
[normal]5
[normal]  The NSPCC study referred to earlier found that as many as one in three girls in Britain have experienced some form of sexual violence from a partner.
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Adult pornography may also be implicated in the development of paedophilia.
[normal]6
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fifthly
[normal], sexual images of women contribute to the pressure on men to assert their masculinity.  They see women vaunting their sexuality and want to show off theirs.  This leads them to 
[normal]engage in loutish behaviour, drink heavily, 
[normal]drive
[normal] recklessly, and so on.  Anti-social behaviour is a big problem in Britain today, and much of it is macho-driven.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sixthly
[normal], pornography contributes to mental illness in society.  Many mental problems have a sexual component.  Emotions are interconnected, and difficulties in one area can lead to problems in another.  Some men have so much difficulty coping with pornography that they have set up a help group, ‘Men and Porn’.  Many suffer 
[normal]on their own,
[normal] and are reluctant to admit that they have sexual problems.  The incidence of mental illness in Britain today is very high and rising.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]While most pornography is aimed at men, it encourages women too to think of sex as something to be pursued as and end in itself, and not just as part of a stable relationship within which children can be brought up.  Pornography aimed at women will do this even more.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Proof[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The contribution of pornography to these various problems is evidenced by the extent to which they have grown over the last sixty years.  Sixty years ago, media standards were high, and there was almost no pornography on sale to the public.  Since then, standards have been relaxed, and the volume and explicitness of pornography have increased.  At the same time, the incidence of all the above problems has grown.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is shown by the following comparisons, taken from my 2005 briefing 
[normal]paper.
[normal]4
[normal]  There
[normal] are large rises in all the indicators from the 1950s to the 2000s.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Teenage pregnancies
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The following chart compares the number of girls in England and Wales becoming pregnant below the age of 14 per thousand members of their age group.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1955 
[normal]|      |
[normal] 0.1
[normal]2002 
