[normal] 1.4
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Family breakdown
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sexual infidelity is one cause of family breakdown.  (Other factors are money, alcohol, and drugs.)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The chart below gives the number of lone parents with dependent children in Britain as a percentage of the total number of families with dependent children.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1955 
[normal]|                |
[normal] 5
[normal]2004 
[normal]|                                                                                       |
[normal] 24
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mental illness
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Sexual problems are one cause of mental illness.  A measure of the level of mental illness in society is the number of anti-depressant drugs people use.  The following chart compares the number of prescription items for these drugs in the community in England per person.  Anti-depressants were introduced in 1957.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1960 
[normal]|     |
[normal] 0.05
[normal]2003 
[normal]|                                                                               |
[normal] 0.55
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Macho violence
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Much of the violence in society is driven by machismo.  Alcohol is often implicated, but heavy drinking by men is 
[normal]itself
[normal], in many cases, macho-driven.  Violence in the media and drugs are other factors.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The chart below compares the number of violent offences against the person recorded by the police in England and Wales per thousand members of the population.  The comparison is only very approximate because the police have changed the way they count violent crimes.  I have doubled the 1955 figure to allow for this.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1955    
[normal]|  |
[normal] 0.4
[normal]2004/5 
[normal]|                                                                                                                    |
[normal] 19.5
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This evidence leaves little doubt that pornography is very harmful.  This finding contradicts the conclusions of Home Office reports on the effects of pornography, published in 1979 and 1990.
[normal]7
[normal]  I have discussed the weaknesses in these reports elsewhere.
[normal]8
[normal]  The biggest one is that they do not answer the question, ‘If pornography is not a major cause of the sexual problems now afflicting society, 
[normal]what is
[normal]?’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A more recent study of hard pornography by the Ministry of Justice concludes that this 
[normal]does
[normal] have a harmful effect on adults.
[normal]9
[normal]  Other recent studies, including one by Dr Linda Papadopoulos for the Home Office, similarly conclude that exposure to pornography has a harmful effect on children.
[normal]10
[normal]  Dr Papadopoulos’ report is alarming.  Would that the proponents of permissiveness in the 1960s had heeded the warnings of those who predicted what the consequences of this would be.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Remedy[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The remedy for these problems is for the Government to enact legislation to restore standards in the media to where they were sixty years ago.  This will be difficult.  Users of pornography will protest, and liberals will complain about loss of freedom.  The above problems are, however, huge and need to be addressed.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]My suggestion is that the Government sets up a Royal Commission to re-examine the effects of pornography and to make recommendations.  Acting on a Royal Commission’s report would be easier for Government than acting on its own.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I have answered objections to raising standards and discussed possible legislation 
[normal]elsewhere.
[normal]11
[normal]  The
[normal] answer to the objection of loss of freedom is that pornography takes away even more freedom – from women who would like to be able to go out alone at night, from young mothers who would like to do what their other friends do, from men who find pornography addictive, from old people shut in for fear of macho-driven yobs, and so on.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Pornography makes for a less civilized society.  It is an evil, and needs to be treated as such.
[normal]&#xa0;
